const title = "1–3 Month Old Sleep: What to Expect and Is It Normal?";
const description = "Babies 1–3 months old sleep 14–17 hours per day in short stretches with no established schedule. Learn what's normal, how to support healthy sleep habits, and safe sleep guidelines for this stage.";

const faqs = [
  {
    question: "How much sleep does a 1–3 month old need?",
    answer: "Most babies between 1 and 3 months need between 14 and 17 hours of total sleep in a 24-hour period, according to the National Sleep Foundation. This sleep is spread across the day and night in multiple short stretches, typically 2–4 hours at a time. Very few babies this age will sleep through the night.",
  },
  {
    question: "Is it normal for my 2-month-old to still wake every 2–3 hours?",
    answer: "Yes, this is completely normal. Babies this age have small stomachs and high caloric needs, so nighttime feedings are both expected and necessary. Most pediatricians do not recommend attempting to reduce nighttime feedings before 4–6 months unless advised to do so for medical reasons.",
  },
  {
    question: "When can I let my baby sleep in a longer stretch at night?",
    answer: "Many babies begin producing longer nighttime stretches (4–6+ hours) somewhere between 6 and 12 weeks, though this varies widely. If your pediatrician has confirmed your baby is gaining weight well, you may be given the green light to stop waking them for night feeds. However, if weight gain is a concern, your baby may need to be woken to feed every 2–3 hours until they're back on track.",
  },
  {
    question: "Should my 1–3 month old be on a sleep schedule?",
    answer: "Not yet. Babies under 3 months do not have an established circadian rhythm, so they cannot follow a predictable clock-based schedule. Instead, focus on responding to sleepy cues (eye rubbing, yawning, staring blankly) and keeping wake windows short — around 45 to 90 minutes. Consistent routines (a short sequence before each sleep) can begin as early as 6–8 weeks.",
  },
  {
    question: "When should I stop swaddling my baby?",
    answer: "You should stop swaddling as soon as your baby shows any signs of trying to roll over. For most babies, this begins between 3 and 4 months. Swaddling a rolling baby is a safety risk because they can roll onto their stomach and be unable to push up or turn themselves back over. Transition to a sleep sack with free arms at that point.",
  },
  {
    question: "Is it safe to let my newborn sleep on my chest?",
    answer: "While skin-to-skin contact is beneficial for bonding and calming a fussy baby, it is not safe as a sleep surface. The AAP recommends that babies always sleep on a flat, firm surface on their backs — a crib, bassinet, or play yard — not on a parent's chest, in an armchair, or on a couch. If you fall asleep while feeding or holding your baby, gently move them to their safe sleep space as soon as you wake.",
  },
